        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>291</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0040</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0040.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Closed linear span">Closed linear span</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The closed linear span of a subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> of a normed vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> is the closure of the linear span of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>The linear span of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[span(S)]]></fr:tex>, is the set of all finite linear combinations of elements in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[span(S) = \{\sum _{i=1}^n a_i v_i : n \in  \mathbb {N}, a_i \in  \mathbb {K}, v_i \in  S\}]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>The closure of a set in a normed space is the set together with all its limit points. So the closed linear span of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, often denoted by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {span(S)}]]></fr:tex>, consists of all vectors that can be approximated arbitrarily well by finite linear combinations of elements in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In the context of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0030.xml" addr="FA-0030" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link>, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0053.xml" addr="FA-0053" title="Orthonormal set">orthonormal set</fr:link>, then a vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> is in the closed linear span of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> if and only if:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v = \sum _i \langle  v, e_i \rangle  e_i]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>where the sum converges in the norm.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>293</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0072</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0072.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Completeness of orthonormal set">Completeness of orthonormal set</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>An <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0073.xml" addr="FA-0073" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal set</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U = \{x_n : n âˆˆ N\}]]></fr:tex> of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0030.xml" addr="FA-0030" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> H is <fr:em>complete (note that this is <fr:strong>not</fr:strong> in the sense of a complete metric <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0048.xml" addr="FA-0048" title="Space">space</fr:link>)</fr:em>  if it satisfies <fr:em>any</fr:em> of the equivalent conditions (a)-(e) in <fr:strong>Theorem</fr:strong>:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U = \{u_n : n \in  \mathbb {N}\}]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0029.xml" addr="FA-0029" title="Orthonormal sequence">orthonormal sequence</fr:link> of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0030.xml" addr="FA-0030" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>, then the following conditions are equivalent:</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(a)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  u_n, x \rangle  = 0]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n \in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = 0]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(b)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = \sum _{n \in  \mathbb {N}} \langle  u_n, x \rangle  u_n]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(c)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x||^2 = \sum _{n \in  \mathbb {N}} |\langle  u_n, x \rangle |^2]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  H]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>(This is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0046.xml" addr="FA-0046" title="Parseval's identity">Parseval's identity</fr:link>)</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(d)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[U] = H]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>(e)</fr:strong> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0076.xml" addr="FA-0076" title="Maximal orthonormal set">maximal</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0029.xml" addr="FA-0029" title="Orthonormal sequence">orthonormal sequence</fr:link></fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:strong>Informally</fr:strong>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>For an orthonormal set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u_\alpha ]]></fr:tex> in a Hilbert space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> to be a <fr:strong>basis</fr:strong> (or complete), it means that the set is "<fr:em>large enough</fr:em>" to represent any vector in the space.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>An <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0029.xml" addr="FA-0029" title="Orthonormal sequence">orthonormal sequence</fr:link> is <fr:em>complete</fr:em> if it's <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0040.xml" addr="FA-0040" title="Closed linear span">closed linear span</fr:link> is the whole space</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>295</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0030</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0030.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hilbert Space">Hilbert Space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A Hilbert space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0023.xml" addr="FA-0023" title="Complete">complete</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0038.xml" addr="FA-0038" title="Inner product space">inner product space</fr:link>. That is, a Hilbert space is a vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> with an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0039.xml" addr="FA-0039" title="Inner product">inner product</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[<\cdot ,\cdot >]]></fr:tex> such that the norm defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||x|| = \sqrt {<x,x>}]]></fr:tex> makes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> into a complete metric space.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Hilbert spaces extend the methods of linear algebra to infinite-dimensional settings, making them crucial for quantum mechanics, Fourier analysis, and partial differential equations.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Examples include the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2]]></fr:tex> of square-integrable functions and the space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[l^2]]></fr:tex> of square-summable sequences.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>297</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0005</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0005.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Infinite Dimensions">Infinite Dimensions</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A vector space is said to be infinite-dimensional if it cannot be spanned by a finite number of vectors. In other words, there is no finite basis for the space.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Examples include function spaces like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C([a,b])]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p]]></fr:tex> spaces, sequence spaces, and Hilbert spaces like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[l^2]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>299</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0073</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0073.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Orthonormal">Orthonormal</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A set of vectors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> in an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0038.xml" addr="FA-0038" title="Inner product space">inner product space</fr:link> is said to be orthonormal if:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>Each vector has unit norm: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[||e_i|| = 1]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Different vectors are orthogonal to each other: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  e_i, e_j \rangle  = 0]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i \neq  j]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>Equivalently, a set of vectors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is orthonormal if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\langle  e_i, e_j \rangle  = \delta _{ij}]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta _{ij}]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0037.xml" addr="FA-0037" title="Kronecker delta">Kronecker delta</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Orthonormal sets have several important properties:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>They are linearly independent</fr:li>
<fr:li>They provide simple formulas for decomposing vectors: If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is an orthonormal set and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> is a vector in the space, then the projection of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> onto the span of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P_{\text {span}\{e_i\}}(x) = \sum _i \langle  x, e_i \rangle  e_i]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li><fr:link type="local" href="FA-0032.xml" addr="FA-0032" title="Bessel's inequality">Bessel's inequality</fr:link> holds: For any vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> and orthonormal set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sum _i |\langle  x, e_i \rangle |^2 \leq  ||x||^2]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
            <fr:p>Orthonormal sets are fundamental in the study of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0030.xml" addr="FA-0030" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert spaces</fr:link> and form the basis for many results in functional analysis, such as the theory of Fourier series and orthogonal polynomials.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>301</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0079</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0079.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Orthonormal Basis">Orthonormal Basis</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A complete (in the sense of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0072.xml" addr="FA-0072" title="Completeness of orthonormal set">Completeness of orthonormal set</fr:link>) <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0073.xml" addr="FA-0073" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> subset (<fr:link type="local" href="FA-0029.xml" addr="FA-0029" title="Orthonormal sequence">orthonormal sequence</fr:link>) of H is also called an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0073.xml" addr="FA-0073" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0074.xml" addr="FA-0074" title="Basis">basis</fr:link> of H</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Altenately</fr:strong>: An <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0073.xml" addr="FA-0073" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0074.xml" addr="FA-0074" title="Basis">basis</fr:link> of H is a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0075.xml" addr="FA-0075" title="Countable">countable</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0076.xml" addr="FA-0076" title="Maximal orthonormal set">maximal</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0073.xml" addr="FA-0073" title="Orthonormal">orthonormal</fr:link> subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_n\}]]></fr:tex> of H.</fr:p>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>N.B.</fr:strong>: This notion of <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0074.xml" addr="FA-0074" title="Basis">basis</fr:link> is <fr:em>not quite the same</fr:em> as in the <fr:em>finite dimensional case</fr:em> (although it is a legitimate extension of it).</fr:p>
            <fr:p>There are other, quite different, notions of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0074.xml" addr="FA-0074" title="Basis">basis</fr:link> in <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0005.xml" addr="FA-0005" title="Infinite Dimensions">infinite dimensions</fr:link>. See for instance '<fr:link type="local" href="FA-0077.xml" addr="FA-0077" title="Hamel basis">Hamel basis</fr:link>' which arises in some settings</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:strong>Theorem:</fr:strong>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>Every <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0078.xml" addr="FA-0078" title="Separable space">separable</fr:link> <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0030.xml" addr="FA-0030" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> has a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0075.xml" addr="FA-0075" title="Countable">countable</fr:link> orthonormal <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0074.xml" addr="FA-0074" title="Basis">basis</fr:link>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>303</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">FA-0046</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>FA-0046.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Parseval's identity">Parseval's identity</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U = \{u_n : n \in  \mathbb {N}\}]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0045.xml" addr="FA-0045" title="Orthonormal Basis">orthonormal basis</fr:link> of a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0030.xml" addr="FA-0030" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = \sum _{n \in  \mathbb {N}} a_n u_n]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y = \sum _{n \in  \mathbb {N}} b_n u_n]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_n = \langle  u_n, x \rangle ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b_n = \langle  u_n, y \rangle ]]></fr:tex>, then</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[{\langle  x, y \rangle  = \sum _{n \in  \mathbb {N}} a_n \bar {b}_n}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p><fr:strong>Alternatively</fr:strong>: Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> be a Hilbert Space and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_n\}]]></fr:tex> be a countable orthonormal basis of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex>, then for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u \in  H]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[{\sum _n {|{\langle  u, e_n \rangle }}|^2 = {||u||}^2}]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>(In <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0032.xml" addr="FA-0032" title="Bessel's inequality">Bessel's inequality</fr:link>, we only had an inequality <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\leq ]]></fr:tex> in the expression above)</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
